  "doc_id": "18630",
  "text": "Flow cytometric analysis showed that in terminal ileum and peripheral blood there was a decreased fraction of B cells with a naive phenotype and a corresponding increase in B cells with a memory B cell and plasma cell phenotype [CITATION_1] . In particular, the fraction of circulating B cells with a plasmablast or plasma cell phenotype was higher in patients with acute or early HIV-1 infection [CITATION_2] , in some patients higher than the fraction reported for other models of antigen stimulation, such as influenza immunization [CITATION_3] . The reason for this increase in circulating plasma cells in acute or early HIV-1 infection is not known, but it may be due to the high levels of cytokines circulating during early infection [CITATION_4] . At this time, work is ongoing to determine the significance of the plasmacytosis observed during acute or early HIV-1 infection and to compare it with that seen in other disease and vaccination models.",
